[236.777472, "o", "              fully.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--init-file \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfile\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--rcfile \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfile\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Execute  commands  from  \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m instead of the system wide ini‐\u001b[m\r\n              tialization file \u001b[4m/etc/bash.bashrc\u001b[24m and the  standard  personal\u001b[m\r\n              initialization  file  \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m  if  the shell is interactive\u001b[m\r\n              (see \u001b[1mINVOCATION \u001b[22mbelow).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--login\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Equivalent to \u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--noediting\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 73 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[237.610766, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[237.612722, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       environment, the \u001b[1mSHELLOPTS\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mBA\u001b[7mSHOPT\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1mS\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mCDPATH\u001b[22m, and  \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE  \u001b[22mvari‐\u001b[m\r\n       ables,  if  they appear in the environment, are ignored, and the ef‐\u001b[m\r\n       fective user id is set to the real user id.  If  the  \u001b[1m-p  \u001b[22moption  is\u001b[m\r\n       supplied  at  invocation,  the startup behavior is the same, but the\u001b[m\r\n       effective user id is not reset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDEFINITIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The following definitions are used throughout the rest of this docu‐\u001b[m\r\n       ment.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mblank  \u001b[22mA space or tab.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mword   \u001b[22mA sequence of characters considered as a single unit  by  the\u001b[m\r\n              shell.  Also known as a \u001b[1mtoken\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mname   \u001b[22mA  \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m consisting only of alphanumeric characters and under‐\u001b[m\r\n              scores, and beginning with an alphabetic character or an  un‐\u001b[m\r\n              derscore.  Also referred to as an \u001b[1midentifier\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmetacharacter\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A character that, when unquoted, separates words.  One of the\u001b[m\r\n              following:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m|  & ; ( ) < > space tab newline\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 216 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[238.247516, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[238.248696, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       environment.  If the \u001b[1mlastpipe \u001b[22moption  is  enabled  using  the  \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin  (see the description of \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbelow), the last element of a\u001b[m\r\n       pipeline may be run by the shell process when job control is not ac‐\u001b[m\r\n       tive.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mLists\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is a sequence of one or more pipelines separated  by  one  of\u001b[m\r\n       the  operators  \u001b[1m;\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m&\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m&&\u001b[22m, or \u001b[1m||\u001b[22m, and optionally terminated by one of\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m;\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m&\u001b[22m, or \u001b[1m<newline>\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Of these list operators, \u001b[1m&& \u001b[22mand \u001b[1m|| \u001b[22mhave equal  precedence,  followed\u001b[m\r\n       by \u001b[1m; \u001b[22mand \u001b[1m&\u001b[22m, which have equal precedence.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A sequence of one or more newlines may appear in a \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m instead of a\u001b[m\r\n       semicolon to delimit commands.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If a command is terminated by the control operator \u001b[1m&\u001b[22m, the shell exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cutes  the  command in the \u001b[4mbackground\u001b[24m in a subshell.  The shell does\u001b[m\r\n       not wait for the command to finish, and  the  return  status  is  0.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 305 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[239.552409, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K       These  are referred to as \u001b[4masynchronous\u001b[24m commands.  Commands separated\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 306 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[239.956502, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[239.95984, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       \u001b[1mteractive_comments \u001b[22moption to the \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbuiltin is enabled (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN COMMANDS \u001b[22mbelow), a word beginning with \u001b[1m#  \u001b[22mcauses  that  word\u001b[m\r\n       and  all remaining characters on that line to be ignored.  An inter‐\u001b[m\r\n       active shell without the \u001b[1minteractive_comments  \u001b[22moption  enabled  does\u001b[m\r\n       not  allow  comments.   The \u001b[1minteractive_comments \u001b[22moption is on by de‐\u001b[m\r\n       fault in interactive shells.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mQUOTING\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mQuoting\u001b[24m is used to remove the special meaning of certain  characters\u001b[m\r\n       or  words  to  the  shell.   Quoting  can be used to disable special\u001b[m\r\n       treatment for special characters, to prevent reserved words from be‐\u001b[m\r\n       ing recognized as such, and to prevent parameter expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Each of the \u001b[4mmetacharacters\u001b[24m listed above under \u001b[1mDEFINITIONS  \u001b[22mhas  spe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cial  meaning  to the shell and must be quoted if it is to represent\u001b[m\r\n       itself.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When the command history expansion facilities are  being  used  (see\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTORY  EXPANSION  \u001b[22mbelow), the \u001b[4mhistory\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m character, usually\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 615 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[240.310552, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[240.312021, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbuiltin, translated strings are single-quoted instead of  dou‐\u001b[m\r\n       ble-quoted.   See the description of \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbelow under \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[22mBUILTIN‐\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is an entity that stores values.  It can be  a  \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m,  a\u001b[m\r\n       number,  or one of the special characters listed below under \u001b[1mSpecial\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mParameters\u001b[22m.  A \u001b[4mvariable\u001b[24m is a parameter denoted by a \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m.   A  vari‐\u001b[m\r\n       able  has  a  \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m and zero or more \u001b[4mattributes\u001b[24m.  Attributes are as‐\u001b[m\r\n       signed using the \u001b[1mdeclare \u001b[22mbuiltin command (see \u001b[1mdeclare \u001b[22mbelow in \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN COMMANDS\u001b[22m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A parameter is set if it has been assigned a value.  The null string\u001b[m\r\n       is a valid value.  Once a variable is set, it may be unset  only  by\u001b[m\r\n       using the \u001b[1munset \u001b[22mbuiltin command (see \u001b[1mSHELL BUILTIN COMMANDS \u001b[22mbelow).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4mvariable\u001b[24m may be assigned to by a statement of the form\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m=[\u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 708 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[240.999672, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 709 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[241.449748, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[241.451201, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       \u001b[1mBA\u001b[7mSHOPT\u001b[27m\u001b[1mS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A colon-separated list of enabled shell options.   Each  word\u001b[m\r\n              in  the  list  is  a  valid argument for the \u001b[1m-s \u001b[22moption to the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbuiltin command (see  \u001b[1mSHELL  BUILTIN  COMMANDS  \u001b[22mbelow).\u001b[m\r\n              The options appearing in \u001b[1mBA\u001b[7mSHOPT\u001b[27m\u001b[1mS \u001b[22mare those reported as \u001b[4mon\u001b[24m by\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m.   If  this  variable  is  in the environment when \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              starts up, each shell option in the list will be enabled  be‐\u001b[m\r\n              fore reading any startup files.  This variable is read-only.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASHPID\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Expands  to the process ID of the current \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mprocess.  This\u001b[m\r\n              differs from \u001b[1m$$ \u001b[22munder certain  circumstances,  such  as  sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              shells  that  do  not require \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mto be re-initialized.  As‐\u001b[m\r\n              signments to \u001b[1mBASHPID \u001b[22mhave no effect.  If \u001b[1mBASHPID \u001b[22mis unset, it\u001b[m\r\n              loses its special properties, even if it is subsequently  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ALIASES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An associative array variable whose members correspond to the\u001b[m\r\n              internal  list of aliases as maintained by the \u001b[1malias \u001b[22mbuiltin.\u001b[m\r\n              Elements added to this array appear in the alias  list;  how‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 857 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[243.002929, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[243.003145, "o", "              ever,  unsetting  array  elements  currently  does  not cause\u001b[m\r\n              aliases to be removed from the alias list.   If  \u001b[1mBASH_ALIASES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              is unset, it loses its special properties, even if it is sub‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 860 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[243.408392, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K              sequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 861 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[243.752402, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBASH_ARGC\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 862 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[244.074642, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[244.074955, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              scription of the \u001b[1mextdebug \u001b[22moption to the \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbuiltin below).\u001b[m\r\n              Setting \u001b[1mextdebug \u001b[22mafter the shell has  started  to  execute  a\u001b[m\r\n              script,  or  referencing  this  variable when \u001b[1mextdebug \u001b[22mis not\u001b[m\r\n              set, may result in inconsistent values.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An array variable containing all of  the  parameters  in  the\u001b[m\r\n              current  \u001b[1mbash  \u001b[22mexecution  call stack.  The final parameter of\u001b[m\r\n              the last subroutine call is at the  top  of  the  stack;  the\u001b[m\r\n              first parameter of the initial call is at the bottom.  When a\u001b[m\r\n              subroutine  is  executed,  the parameters supplied are pushed\u001b[m\r\n              onto \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV\u001b[22m.  The shell sets \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV \u001b[22monly  when  in  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              tended  debugging  mode  (see the description of the \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              option to the \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbuiltin below).  Setting  \u001b[1mextdebug  \u001b[22mafter\u001b[m\r\n              the  shell  has  started  to execute a script, or referencing\u001b[m\r\n              this variable when \u001b[1mextdebug \u001b[22mis not set, may result in  incon‐\u001b[m\r\n              sistent values.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV0\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              When  referenced,  this  variable  expands to the name of the\u001b[m\r\n              shell or shell script (identical to \u001b[1m$0\u001b[22m; see  the  description\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 888 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[244.527018, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[244.527949, "o", "              of  special  parameter  0  above).   Assignment to \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV0\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              causes the value assigned to also  be  assigned  to  \u001b[1m$0\u001b[22m.   If\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV0 \u001b[22mis unset, it loses its special properties, even if\u001b[m\r\n              it is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_CMDS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An associative array variable whose members correspond to the\u001b[m\r\n              internal  hash  table  of  commands as maintained by the \u001b[1mhash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              builtin.  Elements added to this array appear in the hash ta‐\u001b[m\r\n              ble; however, unsetting array  elements  currently  does  not\u001b[m\r\n              cause  command  names  to be removed from the hash table.  If\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_CMDS \u001b[22mis unset, it loses its special properties, even  if\u001b[m\r\n              it is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 900 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[244.907353, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[244.90997, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              \u001b[1mcompat42  \u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22moption and set the compatibility level to 42.\u001b[m\r\n              The current version is also a valid value.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ENV\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If this parameter is set  when  \u001b[1mbash  \u001b[22mis  executing  a  shell\u001b[m\r\n              script,  its  value  is  interpreted as a filename containing\u001b[m\r\n              commands to initialize the shell, as in \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m.  The value\u001b[m\r\n              of \u001b[1mBASH_ENV \u001b[22mis subjected to parameter expansion, command sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              stitution, and arithmetic expansion before being  interpreted\u001b[m\r\n              as  a filename.  \u001b[1mPATH \u001b[22mis not used to search for the resultant\u001b[m\r\n              filename.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_XTRACEFD\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to an integer corresponding to a valid  file  descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n              tor,  \u001b[1mbash  \u001b[22mwill write the trace output generated when \u001b[4mset\u001b[24m \u001b[4m-x\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              is enabled to that file descriptor.  The file  descriptor  is\u001b[m\r\n              closed  when  \u001b[1mBASH_XTRACEFD \u001b[22mis unset or assigned a new value.\u001b[m\r\n              Unsetting \u001b[1mBASH_XTRACEFD \u001b[22mor  assigning  it  the  empty  string\u001b[m\r\n              causes  the  trace  output  to be sent to the standard error.\u001b[m\r\n              Note that setting \u001b[1mBASH_XTRACEFD \u001b[22mto 2 (the standard error file\u001b[m\r\n              descriptor) and then unsetting it will result in the standard\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1173 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[245.26586, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[245.270559, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m,  any  unquoted  instances  of \u001b[1m& \u001b[22min \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m are replaced\u001b[m\r\n              with the matching portion of \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Quoting any part of \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m inhibits replacement in the expan‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion of the quoted  portion,  including  replacement  strings\u001b[m\r\n              stored  in  shell  variables.   Backslash  will  escape  \u001b[1m& \u001b[22min\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m; the backslash is removed in order to permit a literal\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m& \u001b[22min the replacement string.  Backslash can also be  used  to\u001b[m\r\n              escape  a backslash; \u001b[1m\\\\ \u001b[22mresults in a literal backslash in the\u001b[m\r\n              replacement.  Users should take care  if  \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m  is  double-\u001b[m\r\n              quoted  to  avoid unwanted interactions between the backslash\u001b[m\r\n              and  double-quoting,  since  backslash  has  special  meaning\u001b[m\r\n              within  double  quotes.   Pattern  substitution  performs the\u001b[m\r\n              check for unquoted \u001b[1m& \u001b[22mafter expanding \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m;  shell  program‐\u001b[m\r\n              mers  should quote any occurrences of \u001b[1m& \u001b[22mthey want to be taken\u001b[m\r\n              literally in the replacement and ensure any  instances  of  \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              they want to be replaced are unquoted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If the \u001b[1mnocasematch \u001b[22mshell option is enabled, the match is per‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1938 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[245.710689, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[245.712591, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       \u001b[1mtern  Matching\u001b[22m.   See  the  description  of  \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbelow under \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN COMMANDS \u001b[22mfor a  description  of  the  \u001b[1mnocaseglob\u001b[22m,  \u001b[1mnullglob\u001b[22m,\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mglobskipdots\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mfailglob\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1mdotglob \u001b[22mshell options.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE  \u001b[22mshell  variable  may be used to restrict the set of\u001b[m\r\n       file names matching a \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m.  If \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE \u001b[22mis set, each  matching\u001b[m\r\n       file name that also matches one of the patterns in \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE \u001b[22mis re‐\u001b[m\r\n       moved  from  the  list of matches.  If the \u001b[1mnocaseglob \u001b[22moption is set,\u001b[m\r\n       the matching against the patterns in \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE \u001b[22mis performed without\u001b[m\r\n       regard to case.  The filenames \u001b[1m``.''  \u001b[22mand \u001b[1m``..''  \u001b[22mare always ignored\u001b[m\r\n       when \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE \u001b[22mis set and not null.  However, setting \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE \u001b[22mto\u001b[m\r\n       a non-null value has the effect of enabling the  \u001b[1mdotglob  \u001b[22mshell  op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion, so all other filenames beginning with a \u001b[1m``.''  \u001b[22mwill match.  To\u001b[m\r\n       get  the  old behavior of ignoring filenames beginning with a \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[22m,\u001b[m\r\n       make \u001b[1m``.*''  \u001b[22mone of the patterns in \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[22m.  The \u001b[1mdotglob  \u001b[22moption\u001b[m\r\n       is  disabled  when \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE \u001b[22mis unset.  The pattern matching honors\u001b[m\r\n       the setting of the \u001b[1mextglob \u001b[22mshell option.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPattern Matching\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2158 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[246.310254, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[246.311144, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       If  the \u001b[1mextglob \u001b[22mshell option is enabled using the \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mbuiltin, the\u001b[m\r\n       shell recognizes several extended pattern  matching  operators.   In\u001b[m\r\n       the  following  description, a \u001b[4mpattern-list\u001b[24m is a list of one or more\u001b[m\r\n       patterns separated by a \u001b[1m|\u001b[22m.  Composite patterns may be  formed  using\u001b[m\r\n       one or more of the following sub-patterns:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m?(\u001b[4m\u001b[22mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches zero or one occurrence of the given patterns\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m*(\u001b[4m\u001b[22mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches zero or more occurrences of the given patterns\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m+(\u001b[4m\u001b[22mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches one or more occurrences of the given patterns\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m@(\u001b[4m\u001b[22mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches one of the given patterns\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m!(\u001b[4m\u001b[22mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1"]
[246.31123, "o", "m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches anything except one of the given patterns\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The\u001b[1mextglob  \u001b[22moption  changes  the  behavior  of the parser, since the\u001b[m\r\n       parentheses are normally treated as operators with  syntactic  mean‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2231 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[247.318083, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[247.320105, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       the \u001b[1mexpand_aliases \u001b[22mshell option is set using \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m \u001b[22m(see the descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion of \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22munder \u001b[1mSHELL BUILTIN COMMANDS \u001b[22mbelow).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The rules concerning the definition and use of aliases are  somewhat\u001b[m\r\n       confusing.   \u001b[1mBash  \u001b[22malways reads at least one complete line of input,\u001b[m\r\n       and all lines that make up a compound command, before executing  any\u001b[m\r\n       of  the  commands on that line or the compound command.  Aliases are\u001b[m\r\n       expanded when a command is read, not when it  is  executed.   There‐\u001b[m\r\n       fore, an alias definition appearing on the same line as another com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand does not take effect until the next line of input is read.  The\u001b[m\r\n       commands  following  the  alias  definition on that line are not af‐\u001b[m\r\n       fected by the new alias.  This behavior is also an issue when  func‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions are executed.  Aliases are expanded when a function definition\u001b[m\r\n       is read, not when the function is executed, because a function defi‐\u001b[m\r\n       nition  is itself a command.  As a consequence, aliases defined in a\u001b[m\r\n       function are not available until after that  function  is  executed.\u001b[m\r\n       To  be safe, always put alias definitions on a separate line, and do\u001b[m\r\n       not use \u001b[1malias \u001b[22min compound commands.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2543 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[247.757733, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K       For almost every purpose, aliases are superseded by shell functions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2544 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[248.100909, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[248.103533, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       •      options enabled by \u001b[1m\u001b[7mshopt\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      shell aliases defined with \u001b[1malias\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      various  process IDs, including those of background jobs, the\u001b[m\r\n              value of \u001b[1m$$\u001b[22m, and the value of \u001b[1mPPID\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When a simple command other than a builtin or shell function  is  to\u001b[m\r\n       be  executed, it is invoked in a separate execution environment that\u001b[m\r\n       consists of the following.  Unless otherwise noted, the  values  are\u001b[m\r\n       inherited from the shell.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      the  shell's open files, plus any modifications and additions\u001b[m\r\n              specified by redirections to the command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      the current working directory\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      the file creation mode mask\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2954 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[248.965012, "o", "\r\u001b[K/"]
