[257.358137, "o", "\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K\u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)                   General Commands Manual                   \u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22m[options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022 by the Free Software Foundation,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K       Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22mis an \u001b[1msh\u001b[22m-compatible command language interpreter that  executes\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K       commands read from the standard input or from a file.  \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22malso in‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K       corporates useful features from the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[22m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBash  \u001b[22mis intended to be a conformant implementation of the Shell and\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K       Utilities portion of the IEEE  POSIX  specification  (IE"]
[257.358652, "o", "EE  Standard\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K\u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)                   General Commands Manual                   \u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22m[options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022 by the Free Software Foundation,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K       Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22mis an \u001b[1msh\u001b[22m-compatible command language interpreter that  executes\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K       commands read from the standard input or from a file.  \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22malso in‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K       corporates useful features from the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[22m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBash  \u001b[22mis intended to be a conformant implementation of the Shell and\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K       Utilities portion of the IEEE  PO"]
[257.35929, "o", "SIX  specification  (IEEE  Standard\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H"]
[257.359601, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       tion  of  the  \u001b[1mset \u001b[22mbuiltin command, including \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m, can be used as op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions when the shell is invoked.  In addition, \u001b[1mbash  \u001b[22minterprets  the\u001b[m\r\n       following options when it is invoked:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-c        \u001b[22mIf  the  \u001b[1m-c \u001b[22moption is present, then commands are read from\u001b[m\r\n                 the first non\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27mption argument  \u001b[4mcommand_string\u001b[24m.   If  there\u001b[m\r\n                 are arguments after the \u001b[4mcommand_string\u001b[24m, the first argument\u001b[m\r\n                 is assigned to \u001b[1m$0 \u001b[22mand any remaining arguments are assigned\u001b[m\r\n                 to  the  positional parameters.  The assignment to \u001b[1m$0 \u001b[22msets\u001b[m\r\n                 the name of the shell, which is used in warning and  error\u001b[m\r\n                 messages.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-i        \u001b[22mIf the \u001b[1m-i \u001b[22moption is present, the shell is \u001b[4minteractive\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-l        \u001b[22mMake  \u001b[1mbash  \u001b[22mact as if it had been invoked a"]
[257.359677, "o", "s a login shell\u001b[m\r\n                 (see \u001b[1mINVOCATION \u001b[22mbelow).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-r        \u001b[22mIf the \u001b[1m-r \u001b[22moption is present, the shell becomes  \u001b[4mrestricted\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                 (see \u001b[1mRESTRICTED SHELL \u001b[22mbelow).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-s        \u001b[22mIf the \u001b[1m-s \u001b[22moption is present, or if no arguments remain af‐\u001b[m\r\n                 ter  option  processing,  then  commands are read from the\u001b[m\r\n                 standard input.  This option allows the positional parame‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 24 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[259.614813, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[259.614911, "o", "                 ters to be set when invoking an interactive shell or  when\u001b[m\r\n                 reading input through a pipe.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-v        \u001b[22mPrint shell input lines as they are read.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-x        \u001b[22mPrint commands and their arguments as they are executed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-D        \u001b[22mA  list  of  all  double-quoted  strings  preceded by \u001b[1m$ \u001b[22mis\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 29 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[259.787871, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[259.788462, "o", "...skipping...\r\n                 \u001b[4mshopt_option\u001b[24m is present, \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-O\u001b[27m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m\u001b[1m \u001b[22msets the value of that option;\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[1m+O  \u001b[22munsets it.  If \u001b[4mshopt_option\u001b[24m is not supplied, the names\u001b[m\r\n                 and values of the shell  options  accepted  by  \u001b[1mshopt  \u001b[22mare\u001b[m\r\n                 printed  on the standard output.  If the invocation option\u001b[m\r\n                 is \u001b[1m+O\u001b[22m, the output is displayed in a  format  that  may  be\u001b[m\r\n                 reused as input.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--        \u001b[22mA  \u001b[1m--  \u001b[22msignals the end of options and disables further op‐\u001b[m\r\n                 tion processing.  Any arguments after the \u001b[1m--  \u001b[22mare  treated\u001b[m\r\n                 as  filenames  and arguments.  An argument of \u001b[1m- \u001b[22mis equiva‐\u001b[m\r\n                 lent to \u001b[1m--\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22malso interprets a number of multi-character options.  These op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions must appear on the command line  before  the  single-character\u001b[m\r\n       options to be recognized.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--debugger\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Arrange  for  the  debugger profile to be executed before the\u001b[m\r\n              shell starts.  Turns on extended debugging mode (see the  de‐\u001b[m\r\n              scription of the \u001b[1mextdebug \u001b[22moption to the \u001b[1mshopt \u001b[22mbuiltin below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 55 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[259.960212, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[259.961785, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       An  \u001b[4minteractive\u001b[24m  shell  is  one started without non\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[4m\u001b[24mption arguments\u001b[m\r\n       (unless \u001b[1m-s \u001b[22mis specified) and without the \u001b[1m-c \u001b[22moption,  whose  standard\u001b[m\r\n       input  and  error  are both connected to terminals (as determined by\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4misatty\u001b[24m(3)), or one started with the \u001b[1m-i \u001b[22moption.  \u001b[1mPS1 \u001b[22mis  set  and  \u001b[1m$-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       includes  \u001b[1mi  \u001b[22mif  \u001b[1mbash  \u001b[22mis  interactive, allowing a shell script or a\u001b[m\r\n       startup file to test this state.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The following paragraphs describe  how  \u001b[1mbash  \u001b[22mexecutes  its  startup\u001b[m\r\n       files.   If  any of the files exist but cannot be read, \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mreports\u001b[m\r\n       an error.  Tildes are expanded in filenames as described below under\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mTilde Expansion \u001b[22min the \u001b[1mEXPANSION \u001b[22msection.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mis invoked as an interactive login shell, or as a  non-in‐\u001b[m\r\n       teractive shell with the \u001b[1m--login \u001b[22moption, it first reads and executes\u001b[m\r\n       commands  from  the  file  \u001b[4m/etc/profile\u001b[24m, if that file exists.  After\u001b[m\r\n       reading that file, it looks for \u001b[4m~/.bash_profile\u001b[24m, \u001b[4m~/.bash_login\u001b[24m,  and\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m~/.profile\u001b[24m,  in that order, and reads and executes commands from the\u001b[m\r\n       first one that exists and is readable.  The \u001b[1m--noprofile  \u001b[22moption  may\u001b[m\r\n       be used when the shell is started to inhibit this behavior.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 140 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[260.372756, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[260.378398, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              fore reading any startup files.  This variable is read\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27mnly.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASHPID\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Expands  to the process ID of the current \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mprocess.  This\u001b[m\r\n              differs from \u001b[1m$$ \u001b[22munder certain  circumstances,  such  as  sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              shells  that  do  not require \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mto be re-initialized.  As‐\u001b[m\r\n              signments to \u001b[1mBASHPID \u001b[22mhave no effect.  If \u001b[1mBASHPID \u001b[22mis unset, it\u001b[m\r\n              loses its special properties, even if it is subsequently  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ALIASES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An associative array variable whose members correspond to the\u001b[m\r\n              internal  list of aliases as maintained by the \u001b[1malias \u001b[22mbuiltin.\u001b[m\r\n              Elements added to this array appear in the alias  list;  how‐\u001b[m\r\n              ever,  unsetting  array  elements  currently  does  not cause\u001b[m\r\n              aliases to be removed from the alias list.   If  \u001b[1mBA"]
[260.378519, "o", "SH_ALIASES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              is unset, it loses its special properties, even if it is sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              sequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ARGC\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An  array  variable whose values are the number of parameters\u001b[m\r\n              in each frame of the current \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mexecution call stack.   The\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 864 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[260.986539, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[260.988688, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              in  the list is a valid argument for the \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22moption to the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              builtin command (see \u001b[1mSHELL BUILTIN COMMANDS \u001b[22mbelow).  The  op‐\u001b[m\r\n              tions  appearing in \u001b[1mSHELLOPTS \u001b[22mare those reported as \u001b[4mon\u001b[24m by \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m.  If this variable is in the environment when \u001b[1mbash  \u001b[22mstarts\u001b[m\r\n              up,  each  shell  option  in  the list will be enabled before\u001b[m\r\n              reading any startup files.  This variable is read\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27mnly.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSHLVL  \u001b[22mIncremented by one each time an instance of \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mis started.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSRANDOM\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This variable expands to a 32-bit pseudo-random  number  each\u001b[m\r\n              time  it  is  referenced.  The random number generator is not\u001b[m\r\n              linear on systems that support /dev/urandom or \u001b[4marc4random\u001b[24m, so\u001b[m\r\n              each returned number has no relationship to the numbers  pre‐\u001b[m\r\n              ceding  it.  The random number generator cannot be seeded, so\u001b[m\r\n              assignments to this variable have no effect.  If  \u001b[1mSRANDOM  \u001b[22mis\u001b[m\r\n              unset,  it loses its special properties, even if it is subse‐\u001b[m\r\n              quently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mUID    \u001b[22mExpands to the user ID of the current  user,  initialized  at\u001b[m\r\n              shell startup.  This variable is readonly.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1137 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[261.38539, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K       The  following variables are used by the shell.  In some cases, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       assigns a default value to a variable; these cases are noted below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1140 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[261.893581, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[261.893675, "o", "       \u001b[1mBASH_COMPAT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The value is used to set  the  shell's  compatibility  level.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1142 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[262.073447, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[262.076437, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              if  the  command  \u001b[4mset\u001b[24m  \u001b[4m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m had been executed.  When the\u001b[m\r\n              shell enters \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, it sets this variable if it was  not\u001b[m\r\n              already set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPROMPT_COMMAND\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  this  variable is set, and is an array, the value of each\u001b[m\r\n              set element is executed as a command prior  to  issuing  each\u001b[m\r\n              primary  prompt.   If  this is set but not an array variable,\u001b[m\r\n              its value is used as a command to execute instead.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPROMPT_DIRTRIM\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to a number greater than zero, the value  is  used  as\u001b[m\r\n              the  number  of  trailing directory components to retain when\u001b[m\r\n              expanding the \u001b[1m\\w \u001b[22mand \u001b[1m\\W \u001b[22mprompt string escapes (see  \u001b[1mPROMPTING\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              below).  Characters removed are replaced with an ellipsis.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPS0    \u001b[22mThe value of this parameter is expanded (see \u001b[1mPROMPTING \u001b[22mbelow)\u001b[m\r\n              and  displayed  by interactive shells after reading a command\u001b[m\r\n              and before the command is executed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPS1    \u001b[22mThe value of this parameter is expanded (see \u001b[1mPROMPTING \u001b[22mbelow)\u001b[m\r\n              and used as the primary prompt string.  The default value  is\u001b[m\r\n              ``\u001b[1m\\s-\\v\\$ \u001b[22m''.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1408 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[262.510418, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[262.517371, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       \u001b[1mclare  \u001b[22mbuiltin  below) or the \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m functrace \u001b[22mshell option has been en‐\u001b[m\r\n       abled with the \u001b[1mset \u001b[22mbuiltin (in which case all functions inherit  the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mDEBUG  \u001b[22mand  \u001b[1mRETURN  \u001b[22mtraps), and the \u001b[1mERR \u001b[22mtrap is not inherited unless\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m errtrace \u001b[22mshell option has been enabled.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Variables local to the function  may  be  declared  with  the  \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin  command (\u001b[4mlocal\u001b[24m \u001b[4mvariables\u001b[24m).  Ordinarily, variables and their\u001b[m\r\n       values are shared between the function and its caller.  If  a  vari‐\u001b[m\r\n       able  is  declared \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[22m, the variable's visible scope is restricted\u001b[m\r\n       to that function  and  its  children  (including  the  functions  it\u001b[m\r\n       calls).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In the following description, the \u001b[4mcurrent\u001b[24m \u001b[4mscope\u001b[24m is a currently- exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cuting  function.  Previous scopes consist of that function's caller\u001b[m\r\n       and so on, back to the \"global\" scope, where the shell is  not  exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cuting  any  shell  function.  Consequently, a local variable at the\u001b[m\r\n       current scope is a variable declared  using  the  \u001b[1mlocal  \u001b[22mor  \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtins in the function that is currently executing.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2582 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[263.252694, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K       Local  variables  \"shadow\"  variables with the same name declared at\u001b[m\r\n       previous scopes.  For instance, a local variable declared in a func‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion hides a global variable of the same name:  references  and  as‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2585 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[263.754124, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[263.755802, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-O\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfile\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is owned by the effective user id.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-S \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfile\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is a socket.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m-ef \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfile2\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True  if  \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m  and \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m refer to the same device and inode\u001b[m\r\n              numbers.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m -\u001b[1mnt \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfile2\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m is newer (according to modification date)  than\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m, or if \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m exists and \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m does not.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m \u001b[7m-\u001b[27m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m\u001b[1m\u001b[7mo\u001b[27m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m\u001b[1mt \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfile2\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True  if  \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m  is  older than \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m, or if \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m exists and\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m does not.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptname\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the shell option \u001b[4moptname\u001b[24m is enabled.  See the list of\u001b[m\r\n              options under the description of the \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m  \u001b[22moption  to  the  \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              builtin below.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-v \u001b[4m\u001b[22mvarname\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True  if the shell variable \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m is set (has been assigned\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2786 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[264.840139, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[264.840226, "o", "              a value).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-R \u001b[4m\u001b[22mvarname\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the shell variable \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m is set and is a name  ref‐\u001b[m\r\n              erence.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-z \u001b[4m\u001b[22mstring\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the length of \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m is zero.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mstring\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-n \u001b[4m\u001b[22mstring\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the length of \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m is non-zero.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2796 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[265.712531, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[265.712654, "o", "       \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m== \u001b[4m\u001b[22mstring2\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m= \u001b[4m\u001b[22mstring2\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              True  if  the  strings  are equal.  \u001b[1m= \u001b[22mshould be used with the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2799 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[266.229708, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K              \u001b[1mtest \u001b[22mcommand for POSIX conformance.  When used  with  the  \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              command,  this  performs  pattern matching as described above\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2801 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[266.964472, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[266.967864, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       able.  Line editing can be enabled at any time using the \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m emacs \u001b[22mor\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-o\u001b[27m\u001b[1m vi \u001b[22moptions to the \u001b[1mset \u001b[22mbuiltin (see \u001b[1mSHELL BUILTIN COMMANDS \u001b[22mbelow).\u001b[m\r\n       To turn off line editing after the shell  is  running,  use  the  \u001b[1m+o\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1memacs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1m+o vi \u001b[22moptions to the \u001b[1mset \u001b[22mbuiltin.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mReadline Notation\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       In  this  section,  the  Emacs-style notation is used to denote key‐\u001b[m\r\n       strokes.  Control keys are denoted by C-\u001b[4mkey\u001b[24m, e.g.,  C-n  means  Con‐\u001b[m\r\n       trol-N.   Similarly,  \u001b[4mmeta\u001b[24m  keys  are denoted by M-\u001b[4mkey\u001b[24m, so M-x means\u001b[m\r\n       Meta-X.  (On keyboards without a \u001b[4mmeta\u001b[24m key, M-\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m means  ESC  \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m,  i.e.,\u001b[m\r\n       press  the  Escape key then the \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m key.  This makes ESC the \u001b[4mmeta\u001b[24m \u001b[4mpre‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfix\u001b[24m.  The combination M-C-\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m means ESC-Control-\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m, or press the Escape\u001b[m\r\n       key then hold the Control key while pressing the \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m key.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Readline commands may be given numeric \u001b[4marguments\u001b[24m, which normally act\u001b[m\r\n       as a repeat count.  Sometimes, however, it is the sign of the  argu‐\u001b[m\r\n       ment  that is significant.  Passing a negative argument to a command\u001b[m\r\n       that acts in the forward direction  (e.g.,  \u001b[1mkill-line\u001b[22m)  causes  that\u001b[m\r\n       command  to  act  in  a backward direction.  Commands whose behavior\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3284 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
