[273.713831, "o", "\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K\u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)                   General Commands Manual                   \u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22m[options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022 by the Free Software Foundation,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K       Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22mis an \u001b[1msh\u001b[22m-compatible command language interpreter that  executes\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K       commands read from the standard input or from a file.  \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22malso in‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K       corporates useful features from the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[22m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBash  \u001b[22mis intended to be a conformant implementation of the Shell and\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K       Utilities portion of the IEEE  POSIX  specification  (IE"]
[273.714186, "o", "EE  Standard\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K\u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)                   General Commands Manual                   \u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22m[options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022 by the Free Software Foundation,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K       Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22mis an \u001b[1msh\u001b[22m-compatible command language interpreter that  executes\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K       commands read from the standard input or from a file.  \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22malso in‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K       corporates useful features from the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[22m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBash  \u001b[22mis intended to be a conformant implementation of the Shell and\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K       Utilities portion of the IEEE  PO"]
[273.714958, "o", "SIX  specification  (IEEE  Standard\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H"]
[273.71657, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       mand,  unless  the  \u001b[1m\u001b[7mpipefail\u001b[27m\u001b[1m  \u001b[22moption is enabled.  If \u001b[1m\u001b[7mpipefail\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mis en‐\u001b[m\r\n       abled, the pipeline's return status is the value of the last (right‐\u001b[m\r\n       most) command to exit with a non-zero status, or zero  if  all  com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mands  exit  successfully.   If  the  reserved  word  \u001b[1m!   \u001b[22mprecedes a\u001b[m\r\n       pipeline, the exit status of that pipeline is the  logical  negation\u001b[m\r\n       of the exit status as described above.  The shell waits for all com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mands in the pipeline to terminate before returning a value.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  the  \u001b[1mtime \u001b[22mreserved word precedes a pipeline, the elapsed as well\u001b[m\r\n       as user and system time consumed by its execution are reported  when\u001b[m\r\n       the pipeline terminates.  The \u001b[1m-p \u001b[22moption changes the output format to\u001b[m\r\n       that  specified  by POSIX.  When the shell is in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, it does\u001b[m\r\n       not recognize \u001b[1mtime \u001b[22mas a reserved word if the next token begins  with\u001b[m\r\n       a  `-'.   The \u001b[1mTIMEFORMAT \u001b[22mvariable may be set to a format string that\u001b[m\r\n       specifies how the timing information should be  displayed;  see  the\u001b[m\r\n       description of \u001b[1mTIMEFORMAT \u001b[22munder \u001b[1mShell Variables \u001b[22mbelow.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  the shell is in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, \u001b[1mtime \u001b[22mmay be followed by a newline.\u001b[m\r\n       In this case, the shell displays the total user and system time con‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 280 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[274.709348, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[274.740025, "o", "...skipping...\r\n                      \u001b[1m\u001b[7mpipefail\u001b[27m\u001b[1m\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                              If set, the return value of a pipeline is the\u001b[m\r\n                              value of the last (rightmost) command to exit\u001b[m\r\n                              with a non-zero status, or zero if  all  com‐\u001b[m\r\n                              mands  in  the  pipeline  exit  successfully.\u001b[m\r\n                              This option is disabled by default.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mposix   \u001b[22mChange the behavior of \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22mwhere the default\u001b[m\r\n                              operation differs from the POSIX standard  to\u001b[m\r\n                              match  the  standard  (\u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m).  See \u001b[1mSEE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                              \u001b[1mALSO \u001b[22mbelow for a reference to a document that\u001b[m\r\n                              details how posix mode affects bash's  behav‐\u001b[m\r\n                              ior.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mprivileged\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                              Same as \u001b[1m-p\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mverbose \u001b[22mSame as \u001b[1m-v\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mvi      \u001b[22mUse  a  vi-style  command line editing inter‐\u001b[m\r\n                              face.  This also affects the  editing  inter‐\u001b[m\r\n                              face used for \u001b[1mread -e\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mxtrace  \u001b[22mSame as \u001b[1m-x\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 5887 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[276.248909, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
